  "prompt": "What is the difference between together and with?",
  "response": "\"Together\" and \"with\" are both prepositions that can indicate connection or association, but they are used differently:\n\n\"Together\":\n1. Implies a sense of unity or collective action\n2. Usually means in the same place or doing something at the same time\n3. Can be used as an adverb or adjective\n4. Suggests a closer, more integrated relationship\n\nExamples:\n- We went to the movies together.\n- They worked together on the project.\n- The pieces fit together perfectly.\n\n\"With\":\n1. Indicates accompaniment or association\n2. Suggests someone or something is present or involved\n3. More neutral in describing relationships\n4. Used to show connection, but not necessarily close collaboration\n\nExamples:\n- I went to the store with my friend.\n- She wrote the report with a pencil.\n- The book with the blue cover is mine.\n\nKey difference: \"Together\" suggests more active cooperation or connection, while \"with\" is a more general way of describing accompaniment or association.",
